JIRA actually requires a restart when performing a version upgrade; You must shutdown the previous version and start the new JIRA, pointing to the old database in order for JIRA update all the existing tables and content.

Even though in some cases it can be performed in minutes, this is not feasible for many customers which has offices around the world and requires a 24x7 availability. This way, it would be nice if you could have an option for upgrading JIRA on the fly (or in background) with no restart required. 

This improvement doesn't ask for a upgrade button as requested in JRA-26054. We could deploy a new installation JAR in Tomcat, or un-compress the JIRA standalone tarball into a new directory, or even use an "update" option from the Linux/Windows installer. However, it should be upgraded with no need of a restart.

